---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import TierTable from "../components/TierTable.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../components/CodeBlock.astro";
import CtaButton from "../components/CtaButton.astro";

const attestationReqs = [
  {
    tier: "dc-premium / dc-standard",
    items: [
      "H100 / H200 / B200 in Confidential Compute mode (NVTrust)",
      "Intel TDX or AMD SEV-SNP on the host",
      "Re-attestation every 7 days or on firmware update",
      "Multi-vendor TEE encouraged at the operator level (no single-vendor monoculture risk)",
    ],
  },
  {
    tier: "cloud-rented",
    items: [
      "Same TEE substrate as dc-standard (1–2× H100 PCIe or H200)",
      "Provider-supplied attestation chain accepted if NVTrust + cloud-KDS endorsement present",
      "Higher validator sampling rate (5–10%) compensates for shared substrate",
    ],
  },
  {
    tier: "prosumer",
    items: [
      "RTX 5090 / PRO 6000 — no CC mode available, falls back to stake-anchored verification",
      "Deterministic kernel still required (vLLM determinism or SGLang determinism mode)",
      "Sampling rate at 10%+",
    ],
  },
  {
    tier: "edge / embed-only",
    items: [
      "Mac Studio Ultra, dual 3090, Apple M-series, CPU AVX-512 — no TEE available",
      "Stake-only verification posture; customer accepts weaker guarantees for cheaper pricing",
      "Embed-only tier may opt into L6 zkML for small workloads",
    ],
  },
];

const settlementSplit = [
  { who: "Operator (provider)", pct: "75%", why: "The compute is the product." },
  { who: "Verification work (validators + opML watchers + zkML provers)", pct: "15%", why: "Real GPU work; paid proportional to verification performed and consensus alignment." },
  { who: "Protocol treasury", pct: "5%", why: "Audits, security response, customer integrations. Bounded spend rate (≤ 18-month runway burn)." },
  { who: "Governance stakers", pct: "5%", why: "Only if governance retains a real security function (slashing arbitration, parameter review). Otherwise rolls into the 15% verification slice." },
];

const cliExample = `# Wallet CLI and worker binaries are released after signed
# Forge artifacts exist. Until then, build from the source repositories.
git clone https://github.com/orogen-network/wallet-cli.git
cd wallet-cli
cargo build --release
./target/release/wallet-cli --version

# Planned Forge registration flow
./target/release/wallet-cli register-operator \\
  --coldkey ~/.orogen/coldkey.json \\
  --hotkey  ~/.orogen/hotkey.json \\
  --tier    dc-standard \\
  --gpu-device-cert /etc/nvtrust/h100-cert.bin \\
  --tdx-quote      /etc/tdx/quote.bin \\
  --models  llama-3.1-70b-instruct,mixtral-8x22b-instruct \\
  --region  us-east-1 \\
  --bond    100

# Planned worker start flow
orogen-worker serve \\
  --backend vllm \\
  --determinism on \\
  --kv-strategy radix \\
  --listen 0.0.0.0:7331`;
---

<Base
  title="Operators"
  description="Run a GPU operator on the Orogen network. Six hardware tiers from B200/NVL72 down to Apple M-series. Stake floors, attestation requirements, settlement splits, and a worked example of per-H100 unit economics."
  path="/operators"
>
  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">For operators</p>
    <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl">Run a node. Get paid in USD.</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      Orogen operators are the GPU side of the network. You run an open-source
      inference server (vLLM V1, SGLang, TRT-LLM, llama.cpp), with three
      additions: TEE attestation, deterministic kernels, and the receipt
      sidecar. Per-job settlement is minted in OROG at oracle spot when each job
      finalises, with a default 70% auto-swap to USDC at the protocol AMM.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-crust-800/80 bg-crust-900/40 py-16">
    <div class="container-page">
      <p class="heading-eyebrow">Who can mine</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Six tiers, from datacenter to desk.</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
        Hardware bands span frontier multi-GPU stacks down to Apple Silicon. The
        protocol prices each tier as a multiple of base. Operators self-declare a
        tier at registration; validator probes can challenge a tier claim, and
        sustained SLA breach (&gt;5% requests outside latency bound over 24h, or
        &gt;0.5% failed sampling-replay over 7 days) triggers automatic
        downgrade.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-8">
        <TierTable variant="ops" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">Stake requirements</p>
    <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Skin in the game, scaled to the tier.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      Stake is the L1 verification layer — it's the cost of misbehaving. The at-launch
      parameters: 500 OROG for dc-premium, 100 OROG for dc-standard, 50 OROG for
      cloud-rented, 25 OROG for prosumer, and 0 OROG (small deposit only) for edge and
      embed-only tiers. Slashing is partial-loss for sampling mismatches, full-loss for
      coldkey duplication or fraudulent attestation. Stake unlocks 14 days after
      deregistration, gated by an absence of open challenges.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      Validators must hold <strong class="text-crust-100">10× the operator minimum</strong>
      for the tier they sample. That ratio is the floor; in practice validator
      stake is significantly higher because verification compensation scales
      with active stake (Yuma-weighted). See <a href="/validators">Validators</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-crust-800/80 bg-crust-900/40 py-16">
    <div class="container-page">
      <p class="heading-eyebrow">Attestation</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Hardware roots, multi-vendor.</h2>

      <div class="mt-8 grid gap-5 lg:grid-cols-2">
        {
          attestationReqs.map((b) => (
            <div class="surface-card">
              <h3 class="font-mono text-sm text-magma-300">{b.tier}</h3>
              <ul class="mt-3 list-disc space-y-1.5 pl-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-crust-300">
                {b.items.map((i) => <li>{i}</li>)}
              </ul>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">Settlement split per job</p>
    <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">75 / 15 / 5 / 5.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      Per-job emission is pallet-computed (subject to the year-N cap, the rolling-burn
      elasticity bound, and the 5% supply/year ceiling) and split as follows:
    </p>

    <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-crust-800">
      <table class="prose-table">
        <thead class="bg-crust-900/70">
          <tr>
            <th>Recipient</th>
            <th class="text-right">Share</th>
            <th>Rationale</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {
            settlementSplit.map((r) => (
              <tr>
                <td>{r.who}</td>
                <td class="text-right font-mono text-magma-300">{r.pct}</td>
                <td>{r.why}</td>
              </tr>
            ))
          }
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-crust-500">
      No subnet-owner class. Every recipient slot maps to an operating role.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-crust-800/80 bg-crust-900/40 py-16">
    <div class="container-page">
      <p class="heading-eyebrow">Worked example</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Unit economics: 1× H100 SXM at the dc-standard tier.</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
        Indicative numbers, dollars-per-day. Real numbers depend on customer
        mix, regional cost basis, KV-cache hit rate, and the OROG spot price
        (which the operator-side auto-USDC swap normalises). The same per-GPU
        spread keeps Pearl, Akash, and Render operators in the market today.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-crust-800">
        <table class="prose-table">
          <thead class="bg-crust-900/70">
            <tr>
              <th>Line</th>
              <th class="text-right">Value</th>
              <th>Source / assumption</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Operator cost: 1× H100 SXM all-in (compute + power + bandwidth)</td>
              <td class="text-right font-mono">$48 / day</td>
              <td>Mid-2026 mid-tier cloud rate; on-prem can be 30–50% lower.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Throughput: Llama-3.1-70B FP8, batch-served</td>
              <td class="text-right font-mono">~9,000 tok/s output</td>
              <td>vLLM V1 typical SXM throughput, deterministic kernel applied.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Customer price at dc-standard (0.6× base $0.40 / 1M out)</td>
              <td class="text-right font-mono">$0.24 / 1M out</td>
              <td>Base posture; large customers negotiate sub-base via volume.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Reference billable volume at 50% utilization</td>
              <td class="text-right font-mono">~389M output tok / day</td>
              <td>24h × 4500 tok/s, before routing, verification, and customer demand constraints.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Settlement path</td>
              <td class="text-right font-mono">per verified job</td>
              <td>Customer-side burn, verifier sampling, and protocol settlement are computed by the runtime.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Operator exposure controls</td>
              <td class="text-right font-mono">configurable</td>
              <td>Auto-swap percentage, routing tier, and stake floor are registration parameters.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-crust-500">
        Reference values are design assumptions for capacity planning and
        integration testing. They are not realized operator revenue, not a
        forecast, and not financial guidance.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">Bootstrap</p>
    <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">From source build to registration readiness.</h2>

    <CodeBlock code={cliExample} lang="bash" filename="install.sh" />

    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      The wallet CLI handles coldkey/hotkey ceremony, attestation report
      generation, and on-chain registration. The worker daemon embeds vLLM V1
      (or SGLang / TRT-LLM / llama.cpp for the edge tier) with the
      Orogen-specific plugin loaded. Forge registration and first-job routing
      remain behind the public endpoint, signed-artifact, and validator-probe
      readiness gates.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <CtaButton href="/downloads" variant="primary">Artifact policy</CtaButton>
      <CtaButton href="https://docs.orogen.network" variant="secondary" rel="noopener noreferrer">Operator guide</CtaButton>
      <CtaButton href="/validators" variant="ghost">Validator role</CtaButton>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
